- What do you think about voice control?
A very popular detail, but don't you think you overstate it?
- Of course you can't consider it a panacea, you've got to solve the issue of privacy, as you don't always want others to know about our actions and intentions.
In fact, all types of computer interaction are good, but each in its own field.
For example, for the control of devices in public places, we had a project in which we think about gestures, but not in loose movements, but shorter.
In addition, the gestures were captured not by the device's camera, but by a bracelet that recorded the movement of the bones and muscles.
For now it's very big, but in theory it can be reduced to the size of a wristwatch.
But, in general, the future is for a combined type of control, for example gesture - voice.
- How's that?
- For example, how would you ask me to pass this can of soda?
You will talk and show it at the same time.
- I usually just talk.
- Oh, that's gonna be very hard to recognize.
- I mean, you want to force users to adapt to what the machine can or can't do right now?
Not necessarily, but it's a mutual rapprochement.
I think in the near future we're going to have to work mainly on the design of new types of sensors that can accurately determine the person's reactions.
