Poland and the cosmos.
Poland was accepted as a twelfth member of ESA at the meeting of ministers of the countries of the European Space Agency last week. It is the second ESA member country of the former Eastern European bloc, after the Czech Republic, which became a full member on 12 November 2008).
Poland began intensive collaboration with ESA in 1994 and in subsequent years participated in the agency's project commission.
However, Poland's path to the cosmos began much earlier.
Polish enthusiasts were already engaged in flights into space before World War II, although their work was not always understood.
I remember, for example, the A-conference. Eternfeld at the Warsaw astronomical observatory in which, on 6 December 1933, he presented his ideas on the pioneering study "Introduction to cosmonautics."
The young engineer's ideas (born 1905) left the attendees indifferent and, years later, Eternfeld recalled that Dr. Jan Gadomski had been the only one who had shown interest in his work.
In 1934, Eternfeld won the Robert Esnault-Pelterie and Andr√© Louis Hirsch Award in France for their "Introduction to cosmonautics."
Dr. Jan Gadomski (1899 - 1966), mentioned above, later became a great promoter of astronomy and cosmonautics.
He published hundreds of articles in Polish journals and wrote a series of books dedicated to this scientific discipline.
Gadomski became a promoter of cosmonautics, was known all over the world and his contribution to science was rewarded when he named himself to one of the craters on the hidden face of the moon.
Already in 1925 a dresine was built in Poland that was to be equipped with a rocket engine.
Unfortunately, it is unknown who was the author of the proposal and the project's facilities are not known either.
It is not clear whether the rocket was to be used for the dresin boot or brake.
Information about this dresine is limited to the collection in the press of the time.
From 1933 Polish artillery began to engage in missiles.
The research was funded by Kom√≥rka Techniki Uzbrojenia in collaboration with prof. Mieczyslawem Wolfkem and prof. Gustawem Mokrzyckiegim.
From the preserved material, it becomes clear that the investigation reached the stage of the practical evidence.
However, with the arrival of the German troops, the investigation was interrupted.
In 1937 the prototype of a photoelectric hunting missile designed by engineer Rohoziski appeared in the specialized press and the following year the study "Rakieta - torpea powietrzna i rakietobomba lonicza," by the author Leliwa-Krzyblocki, was published.
Both projects were intended for the military use of missile engines.
Shortly before the war, the Interim Scientific Advisory Committee (Tymccesowy Komitet Doradczo-Naukowy) was responsible for all missile technical projects for military use and coordinated all work.
The committee was founded in 1937, but after two years of activity, it was interrupted by the beginning of the war.
Other studies dedicated to cosmonautics appeared in the Polish press after the war thanks to the work of the Polish Astronautics Society (Polskie Towarzystwo Astronautyczne).
In the November 1954 edition of the magazine Problemy, society is referred for the first time to four very extensive articles dedicated to astronautics.
In one of them, from the prof. M. Subotowicze proposed the creation of a society that would be dedicated to cosmonautics.
Artificial satellite projects had already been launched at that time and it was obvious that cosmic research was a discipline with future prospects.
Since the beginning of 1956, the Polish Society of Astronautics (PTA) aspired to join the International Federation of Astronautics (founded in 1951) and in autumn of the same year the PTA became a full member.
The following year, the first president of the PTA, Kazimierz Zarankiewicz (1902 - 1959), became vice president of the International Federation of Astronautics.
He held this office until his death in 1959.
Beginning in 1956, the PTA participated significantly in the development of the RM probe rocket (Rakieta Meteorologiczna), which was a success and became the first Polish rocket in which scientific research was carried out.
The first type RM-1 was completed in 1957 and was first released on October 10, 1958.
The rocket was at an apoge of 1,800 meters, about 80 cm long and did not reach 5 kg of weight.
Later, the RM-1A version was completed and in summer 1959 aerial tests of the two-stage RM-2 rockets in the desert of Bd√≥w began.
The rocket measured 1.4 meters and weighed about 11.5 kg.
Another type of developing rocket was to be the subject of real scientific study. The RM-34 rocket was going to have a 14.5km heyday and its mission would be to control the high wind.
However, work was suspended in 1962.
The successor to the first RM-type rockets was the Meteor-1 rocket, which was built during 1962 and 1965.
It was designed as a two-stage rocket, with a total length of 510 cm and an initial weight of 32.5 kg.
Three types (called Meteor-1A, -1B and -1C) were developed, which differed from each other by the space available to scientific devices.
On the Meteor-1A rocket the space available for volume was 0.4 liters, in the 0.34 litre Meteor-1B and 0.62 litre Meteor-1C.
The peak in the three types was 37 km.
Between 1965 and 1968, the Meteor-2 rocket was developed at the Air Institute, whose first aerial tests began in October 1970.
The Meteor-2 rocket had an initial weight of 380 kg and was able to carry a useful weight of 10 kg up to 60 km high.
Subsequently, the Meteor-2H and Meteor-3 version was built.
Mention should also be made of Poland &apos; s entry into the COSPAR (Committee for Space Research) in 1960 and the formation of the national committee of COSPAR two years later.
Within the framework of the Interkosmos programme, Poland joined the research of cosmic space on Soviet artificial satellites and, in 1978, Polish pilot Miroslaw Hermaszewski became the second intercosmonaut after Vladim√≠r Remek.
