Bradley Manning did not report mistreatment, prosecutors say
Prosecutors try to deal with Bradley Manning's abuse allegations during his time in prison
Trial focuses on Manning's time at Quantico military prison in Virginia
The defense wants the case dismissed on the grounds that Manning's imprisonment was severe
The Army soldier is accused of stealing thousands of confidential documents.
Prosecutors tried to prove Friday that Private Bradley Manning, accused of the largest leak of confidential information in U.S. history, missed multiple opportunities to report the ill-treatment he now alleges he suffered while in military detention.
During the prosecution's interrogation of Manning at a pre-trial hearing in Ft. Meade, Maryland, prosecutor Commander Ashden Fein said records of weekly visits of officers from the unit Manning received during nine months of detention in Quantico, Virginia, show no complaints about the treatment he received.
The interrogation, which took place during a hearing following the defence's request for the dismissal of the case since his incarceration had been harsh and that this had already meant enough punishment, came a day after Manning had testified that he had thought of suicide while in custody.
The army intelligence analyst, arrested in June 2010, is accused of stealing thousands of confidential documents while on duty in Iraq.
Later, WikiLeaks posted the material on the Internet.
WikiLeaks has never confirmed that Manning was the source of information.
At Friday's hearing, Fein reviewed with Manning the forms that officers filled out after visits to Manning during his arrest at Quantico military prison, where he was imprisoned in maximum detention from July 2010 to April 2011.
Officers reportedly asked Manning questions and scoring his answers.
When Fein asked about the forms on Friday, Manning acknowledged that he had described the treatment given to him by the wardens as "excellent" and the treatment received at the facility in general as "very professional."
The forms do not show any allegations of abuse, even though officers asked Manning directly about the treatment he received, Fein said.
Manning responded that he had expressed concern about some issues and that the visiting officers had spoken about those problems and had indicated that they would be addressed, but that they did not record those issues in the register.
"They wrote 'no incidents' (after talking about the problems) but this doesn't necessarily mean I wouldn't have mentioned any problems," Manning said.
The judge, Army Col. Denise Lind, also asked Manning why he had not reported the treatment he received during the meeting in January 2011 with a council investigating suicide intentions he had expressed in a form months earlier.
Manning replied that his intention during that meeting was to obtain the reduction of the "injury prevention" regime under which he was.
The military said it had put him under that restrictive regime, which is below the basis of surveillance for possible suicide, to ensure its protection and safety of others.
"I wanted the staff to know that I was okay and (I wanted) to stop being under injury prevention ... so I could enjoy what, from my point of view, is a better quality of life," Manning said.
Manning testified Thursday about his arrest in Iraq and his transfer to Kuwait, where he was held for nearly two months before being transferred to the military prison at the Marine base in Quantico, Virginia, in July 2010.
He said he had considered suicide in Kuwait and once lost consciousness due to the heat.
He said the fact that he was not allowed to know what was going on with him or what was going on in the outside world was very distressing.
"My world was reduced only to Camp Arafjon, to that cage," Manning said Thursday.
"I thought I was going to die in that cage".
Manning said that once he moved to Quantico, he spent most days in a small cell, at least 21 hours and often for 23 hours, without company.
Manning said he was only allowed to have a mattress, a blanket, some slippers, some clothes and his glasses.
He explained that he was trying to move all the time, as it was forbidden to sleep or even lie down during the day.
Manning said he always had a light coming from outside pointing his eyes as he slept.
He said if the wardens couldn't see his face when he turned around at night, they would wake him up to turn around again.
Manning's lawyer filed a formal complaint in January 2011 about Manning's treatment.
Manning was transferred to the Fort Leavenworth military prison in Kansas in April 2011.
On Friday, the judge asked Manning about a plea he had made in Thursday's statement that, after being forced one night to sleep naked in his cell in Quantico, he was forced during a morning count to remain naked standing in front of the warden and other prisoners.
Manning had testified that he had never been given a chance to cover himself with the blanket during the count.
During the judge's cross-examination on Friday, Manning said he deduced by the order given to him by the warden that he should drop the blanket with which he could have been covered, but acknowledged that no one had ordered him to drop it.
Manning testified Thursday that he had been forced to sleep naked the night before because of an attempt to prove to an officer that he was not a danger to himself.
Manning said he had told the officer he might have used the elastic of his underwear or his flip-flops to self-harm but had not.
Manning testified that that night his underwear, his flip flops and glasses had been removed from his cell.
His lawyers hope that the judge will at least take into account the experiences he spent during his stay in prison and drastically reduce his sentence in the event that he was convicted in the court martial, which is expected to begin early next year.
The defense said it plans to have Manning plead guilty to misdemeanor and defending other charges deemed too extreme.
The hearing is scheduled to resume this weekend and prosecutors are expected to argue that the conditions of detention were justified.
The Pentagon has argued that Manning was held under the enforcement rules of any detainee who is in high custody in Quantico.
The charges against Manning include cooperation with the enemy, illegally provoking the publication of information on the Internet, leaking national defense information and theft of property or public records.
If convicted of all charges, he could face life in prison.
My Mexican-American identity crisis
He claims that many were forced to leave Mexico due to lack of opportunities
Mexicans tend to criticize those who left; he says they remember Mexicans from those difficult times
Navarrette says Mexican-Americans are trapped between two worlds.
