Posters indicated the way to two queues: one for "Mexicans" and one for "Extranjeros."
I stayed there for a few seconds without being sure where I was supposed to go.
Having grown up in Central California, I have been called "Mexican" all my life.
This is about ethnic typography, just as my Boston friends refer to themselves as "Irish" or my friends in New York call themselves "Italians."
Later I decided on "Mexican-American."
But this was Mexico.
And, in my grandfather's homeland, short-sightshots or scripts were not necessary.
He was simply American.
I speak Spanish. Good enough to handle me during an interview on this language.
But I don't have the vocabulary level of a native and I can't get rid of my American accent.
So I took my American passport and got in the queue of foreigners.
I thought at that time this week when Mexico's president-elect, Enrique Pe√±a Nieto, visited the White House to meet President Obama.
